At this time, `dotnet new globaljson` supports only one argument, `--sdk-version <VERSION NUMBER>`

See <https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/tools/dotnet-new>

It generates a global.json file that looks like this:

```json
{
  "sdk": {
    "version": "5.0.100"
  }
}
```

I always find myself adding a [`rollFoward`](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/tools/global-json?tabs=netcore3x) setting manually like this to keep up with updated SDK's in both development machines and in CI/build machines. 

```json
{
  "sdk": {
    "version": "5.0.100",
    "rollForward": "latestFeature"
  }
}
```

Can we consider adding a `--roll-forward` switch to `dotnet new globaljson`command  with `[patch, feature, minor, major, latestPatch, latestFeature, latestMinor, latestMajor, disable]` options ? 

**Breaking change suggestion**

*This is a breaking change suggestion and needs careful thinking.*

Even better if `dotnet new globaljson` could default to `--roll-forward latestFeature` either in general, or when it detects a non-preview (i.e., a *released*) SDK version (i.e., one referenced through <https://github.com/dotnet/core/blob/master/release-notes/releases-index.json>)

